      "removing `L1[idx1]`, because:\n\n`(l.set idx (L1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = ... = (l.take idx).flatten ++ (L1.eraseIdx idx1).flatten ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ L1.eraseIdx idx1 ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten`, and `(l.set idx L1).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ L1 ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten`. \n\nSince `(L1.eraseIdx idx1).flatten = L1.eraseIdx idx1` (since it's already a list), we can see that `L1.eraseIdx idx1` is the same as `L1` without `L1[idx1]`, but the problem is that the `++` operation doesn't directly work this way (we need to know where to remove `L1[idx1]`).\n\nBut perhaps we can argue that in `(l.take idx).flatten ++ L1 ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten`, if we remove `L1[idx1]`, we get `(l.take idx).flatten ++ (L1.eraseIdx idx1) ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten`, which is exactly `(l.set idx (L1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten`.\n\nBut perhaps we need the notion of `insert` and `erase` to do this.\n\nBut perhaps not, because we can instead consider `pos = (l.take idx).length + idx1`, and then:\n\n`(l.take idx).flatten.length + L1.length = (l.take (idx+1)).",
