      "just taking the sum of lengths of the first `idx` elements of `l`, plus `idx1`. \n\nBut Lean requires `Fin` indices, which are bounded by the length of the list. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can prove that `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = ((l.set idx l1).eraseIdx (some index))` by using that `l1.eraseIdx idx1 = l1.eraseAt idx1`, and that inserting `l1.eraseAt idx1` into the list gives the same as erasing that element.\n\nBut Lean doesn't have `eraseAt` for lists; it has `eraseIdx`. \n\nHowever, perhaps it's better to just calculate the index as `sum of lengths before + idx1` and use that. \n\nBut here is an even better idea:\n\n1. We can actually find the position of `l1[idx1]` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten` by noticing that it's the `idx1`th element of the `l1` part.\n2. Specifically, we can use the following fact:\n   `(l.set idx l1).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ l1 ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`.\n3. So the length of `(l.take idx).flatten` is `S = sum_{i < idx} length (l[i])`.\n4. Then `l1[idx1]` is at position `S + idx1` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten`.\n5. Similarly, `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ (l1.eraseIdx idx1) ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`, and `l1.eraseIdx idx1` is just `l1` without `l1[idx1]`, so we can show that `(l.set idx l1).flatten.erase (S + idx1) = (l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten`.\n\nBut the key is to find `S`. \n\nIn Lean, we can actually define `S` as `(l.take idx).flatten.length`, because `sum_{i < idx} length (l[i]) = (l.take idx).flatten.length`. \n\nThus, the index of `l1[idx1]` is `(l.take idx).flatten.length + idx1`.\n\nBut because Lean uses `Fin`, we need to verify that this index is `< (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`.\n\nIndeed:\n`(l.set idx l1).length = (l.take idx).length + 1 + (l.drop (idx + 1)).length`, but `(l.take idx).flatten.length >= (l.take idx).length`, and more precisely, `(l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length + (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`, but we don't know much about `(l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length`.\n\nHmm, that approach is not directly helpful.\n\nBut perhaps an easier approach is to realize that:\n`(l.set idx l1).flatten.length >= l1.length`, because other parts of the list add up to at least `0`.\n\nThen `(l.take idx).flatten.length + idx1 < (l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length <= (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`.\n\nNo, because `(l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length` could be `0`, but in that case `(l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`, and then `(l.take idx).flatten.length + idx1 < (l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`.\n\nIn general, since `idx1 < l1.length`, `(l.take idx).flatten.length + idx1 < (l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length`, and `(l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length <= (l.take idx).flatten.length + l1.length + (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`.\n\nThus, `(l.take idx).flatten.length + idx1 < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`.\n\nBut perhaps there is a simpler approach?\n\nHere is another idea:\n\n1. Calculate the index of `l1[idx1]` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten`.\n   - Because `(l.set idx l1).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ l1 ++ (l.drop (idx+1)).flatten`, it is clear that the first part has length `S = (l.take idx).flatten.length`, and the position of `l1[idx1]` is `S + idx1`.\n   - But we don't have the `--` operator in Lean for lists, so perhaps it's better to use `take` and `drop` to find the position.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that `(l.take (idx + 1)).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ l[idx]`, and then replace `l[idx]` with `l1`.\n\nBut perhaps it's better to use the `List.get?` function.\n\nHowever, perhaps the simplest way is to use the following trick:\n- In `(l.set idx l1).flatten`, the element `l1[idx1]` is exactly at the position where we can find `l1[idx1]` in the list `l1`, shifted by `(l.take idx).flatten.length`.\n\nWait no, that's not true unless `l1` appears directly after `(l.take idx).flatten`. \n\nBut in `(l.set idx l1).flatten`, the elements of `l1` are inserted exactly where `l[idx]` was, and everything else remains unchanged.\n\nBut perhaps another approach is to realize that `(l.set idx l1).flatten` is the same as:\n`(l.take idx).flatten ++ l1 ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`.\n\nSimilarly, `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten` is `(l.take idx).flatten ++ (l1.eraseIdx idx1) ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`.\n\nNow, notice that `l1.eraseIdx idx1` is `l1.take idx1 ++ l1.drop (idx1 + 1)`.\n\nSo if we let `S = (l.take idx).flatten.length`, then:\n- The length of `(l.set idx l1).flatten` is `S + l1.length + (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length`.\n- The element `l1[idx1]` is at position `S + idx1`.\n- The length of `l1.eraseIdx idx1` is `l1.length - 1`.\n- The length of `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten` is `S + (l1.length - 1) + (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length`.\n\nNow, we can compute:\n`(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = (l.take idx).flatten ++ (l1.take idx1) ++ (l1.drop (idx1 + 1)) ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`\n`= [(l.take idx).flatten ++ (l1.take idx1)] ++ (l1.drop (idx1 + 1)) ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`.\n\nBut also, `(l.set idx l1).flatten.erase (S + idx1)` is `[(l.take idx).flatten ++ (l1.take idx1)] ++ (l1.drop (idx1 + 1)) ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten` because we are deleting the `(S + idx1)`-th element, which is `l1[idx1]`.\n\nBut in Lean, perhaps it's better to use that:\n`(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = (l.set idx l1).flatten.erase (S + idx1)`.\n\nHowever, I think the following would work:\n\n1. Define `S = (l.take idx).flatten.length`.\n2. Then `S + idx1 < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`, because `S + (l1.length + (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten.length) = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length` and `idx1 < l1.length`.",
      "\n      have h₁ : (l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = (l.set idx l1).flatten.eraseIdx (((List.take idx l).flatten).length + (l1.take idx1).length) := by sorry\n      have h₂ : l1[idx1] = (l.set idx l1).flatten.get ⟨((List.take idx l).flatten).length + (l1.take idx1).length, by sorry⟩ := by sorry\n      have h₃ : ((List.take idx l).flatten).length + (l1.take idx1).length < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length := by sorry\n      have h₄ : ∃ (idx' : Fin (l.set idx l1).flatten.length), (l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten = (l.set idx l1).flatten.eraseIdx ↑idx' ∧ l1[idx1] = (l.set idx l1).flatten[idx'] := by sorry\n      exact h₄",
      "\n      have h₁ : ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length), (l1)[idx1] = (l.set idx l1).flatten[i] := by\n        have h₂ : ∀ (l : List (List α)) {l1 : List α} {idx : ℕ}, idx < l.length →\n          ∀ {n : ℕ} (h : n < l1.length) (a : α), a = l1[n] → ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length), a = (l.set idx l1).flatten[i] := by\n          intro l l1 idx hidx h h₂\n          induction l generalizing l1 with\n          | nil =>\n            simp_all\n          | cons hd tl ih =>\n            cases' eq_or_ne idx 0 with h₀ h₀\n            · subst h₀\n              simp_all [List.set, List.forall_cons]\n              <;>\n                (try omega) <;>\n                (try {\n                  have h₃ : n < l1.length := h\n                  have h₄ : l1[n] = l1[n] := rfl\n                  have h₅ : ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten.length), l1[n] = (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten[i] := by\n                    have h₆ : n < l1.length := h₃\n                    have h₇ : ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < l1.length), l1[n] = l1[i] := by\n                      exact ⟨n, by linarith, by simp⟩\n                    obtain ⟨i, hi, h₈⟩ := h₇\n                    have h₉ : i < l1.length := hi\n                    have h₁₀ : l1[i] = l1[i] := rfl\n                    have h₁₁ : ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten.length), l1[n] = (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten[i] := by\n                      have h₁₂ : (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten = (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten := rfl\n                      have h₁₃ : l1[n] = l1[i] := by simp_all\n                      have h₁₄ : ∃ (i : ℕ) (hi : i < (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten.length), l1[n] = (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten[i] := by\n                        have h₁₅ : l1[i] = (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten[i] := by\n                          have h₁₆ : (l1 ++ hd :: tl).flatten = l1.flatten ++ hd ++ tl.flatten := by\n                            simp [List.append_assoc]\n                            <;> rfl\n                          simp_all [List.get, 