      "the length of `l1`.\n   - Similarly for `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten`.\n\n2. **EraseIdx and Flattening**: \n   - `l1.eraseIdx idx1` removes the `idx1`-th element of `l1`.\n   - The difference between `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten` and `(l.set idx l1).flatten` is the removal of `l1[idx1]` from the flattened list.\n\n3. **Key Insight**:\n   - The `l1[idx1]` element appears in `(l.set idx l1).flatten` at a position corresponding to the sum of lengths of elements in `l` before the `idx`-th element plus `idx1`.\n   - Removing `l1[idx1]` is equivalent to erasing that position in `(l.set idx l1).flatten`.\n\n### Step 3: Formal Proof Sketch\n\nTo formalize this, we need to find the correct position `idx'` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten` where `l1[idx1]` occurs. \n\n1. **Calculate Position**:\n   - Let `pre_len = (l.take idx).map List.length |> List.sum`.\n   - The position of `l1[idx1]` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten` is `pre_len + idx1`.\n\n   Proof sketch:\n   - The first `idx` elements of `l` are the same as in `l.set idx l1`, so their lengths are summed to get `pre_len`.\n   - The `l1` in `l.set idx l1` is inserted directly after these elements, so the `idx1`-th element of `l1` is at position `pre_len + idx1`.\n\n2. **Verify**:\n   - Ensure `pre_len + idx1 < (l.set idx l1).flatten.length`, which is true because `pre_len + l1.length = (l.set idx l1).flatten.length` and `idx1 < l1.length`.\n   - The `eraseIdx` at `pre_len + idx1` in `(l.set idx l1).flatten` removes `l1[idx1]` and results in `(l.set idx (l1.eraseIdx idx1)).flatten`.\n\nHowever, formalizing this in Lean requires actual computation of lengths and positions, which can get involved. We will instead use the fact that:\n\n- `(l.set idx l1).flatten` is the same as `(l.take idx).flatten ++ l1 ++ (l.drop (idx + 1)).flatten`.\n- Therefore, `l1[idx1]` is in the middle of this concatenation, and we can find its position by summing lengths appropriately.\n\nBut in Lean, we can instead use the fact t